AB  - This paper analyzes a model of duopoly with heterogeneous goods where behavior patterns are endogenously determined by producers. It is shown that the source of non-equivalence of tariffs and quotas is not the monopolistic behavior of the domestic producer over consumers, but a certain kind of his behavior against the foreign producers. This result is then extended to the cases of a general Nash-type oligopoly and monopolistic competition. The paper also examines how the behavior patterns of the producers are affected by tariffs and quotas and proves non-equivalence of tariffs and quotas in the duopoly situation where the pricing behavior of the producers is endogenously determined by trade policies.
